I think that we can construct a scenario in which the loop never exits.

Consider the case where, right after the CAS and right before we call `jl_lock_stackwalk`, the task gets migrated to another thread. Then we will fail to capture its backtrace in the current loop iteration and will try again in the next loop iteration. If this repeats in the next loop iteration and then over and over again, we will never be able to capture a backtrace and will get stuck in the loop.

While I do recognize that the case I'm describing is exceedingly rare, this still raises the question whether we should prevent a task from getting rescheduled/migrated once we start profiling it.

I believe this may improve the performance of `jl_record_backtrace` by reducing the number of failed attempts of capturing a backtrace, and will likely make the implementation a lot easier to reason about.

